          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>St Louis</placeName>
                                        <date>October 6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1853/5604</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <placeName>Pha</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">With great pleasure I acknowledge<lb/> the receipt
                                        of your favor of the <date>20<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date>
                                        <add>?</add> and thank you for<lb/> the kind inquiries and
                                        friendly wishes concerning my<lb/> father. He arrived last
                                        spring safely in <placeName>New York</placeName> and<lb/> I
                                        met him there we sold parts of the Books he had brought<lb/>
                                        with him though at a sacrifice to some <placeName>N.
                                                  Y.</placeName> hebrew Book<lb/> sellers. This kept
                                        us so long there that I had to forego the pleasure<lb/> of
                                        visiting you in <placeName>Pha</placeName>. And to return
                                        the shortest route to this<lb/> city, where I established
                                        since a pretty large Hardware<lb/> Business. The opening of
                                        this new business deprived me of all<lb/>
                                        <sic>leasure</sic> either to write you and for your monthly,
                                        or to get<lb/> you any subscribers. The latter is moreover a
                                        very difficult<lb/> thing, our correligionaries being either
                                        too indifferent or perhaps<lb/> too poor to pay for it. Of
                                        the two subscribers which you<lb/> mention the one
                                                  (<persName>Mr. Nuttenwieser</persName>) is as you
                                        justly suppose<lb/> either in
                                                  <placeName>California</placeName> or
                                                  <placeName>Europe</placeName>, or may be
                                                  <sic>pedling</sic> among the<lb/> Indians; and the
                                        second (<persName>Mr Block</persName>) is among the
                                        blessed<lb/> that have changed this life for a more perfect
                                        one.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I enclose herewith $5.00, which I hope you
                                        will<lb/> accept as payment in full for the one copy which I
                                        receive</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I will try to get—if possible—payments from the
                                        heirs of<lb/>
                                        <persName>Mr Block</persName> and send you the amount as
                                        soon as received.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">You have the kindness to ask my views on your<lb/>
                                        changing the Occident into a weekly paper. I believe
                                        that<lb/> most of your subscribers will be pleased with such
                                        a change<lb/> and you will probably get some new subscribers
                                        by it, besides<lb/> you would get more <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >advertisements</hi>, the greatest aid for<lb/>
                                        every periodical; but I doubt that it would even then<lb/>
                                        prove a profitable speculation.</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>In my opinion—which may altogether<lb/> wrong—you could succeed if
                                        your paper becomes the<lb/> exponent of the sentiments and
                                        views of the majority of<lb/> our people here, if it adapts
                                        itself to the <add>?</add> of <hi rend="underline"
                                        >our</hi><lb/> times, if it was a paper for <hi
                                                  rend="underline">American</hi> Jews;</p>
                              <p>As an advocate of the Jews of the middle age, of absolute<lb/>
                                        views and customs, of sentiments that exist but in very
                                        few<lb/> (and among these few mostly such as your
                                                  <sic>orthodoxie</sic> will not deem<lb/>
                                        sufficient it will receive but little support).</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">There are among those who support your paper
                                        certainly<lb/> many that differ widely with its views and tendency—but<lb/>
                                        <hi rend="underline">like it</hi> for its undisputed great
                                        merits, for the many excellent<lb/> pages it contains for
                                        the high esteem which they bear to<lb/> it able conductor
                                        notwithstanding this difference of opinions<lb/> and
                                        sentiments in many points.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I hope you will excuse the frankness with
                                        which<lb/> I give you my unpretending opinion</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">and will accept with friendly feelings</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">my best wishes to the next year</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">and the assurance of</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">my respect &amp; affection,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">with which I remain yours</p>
                              <p rend="indent(6)">
                                        <persName role="author">Isidor Bush</persName>
                              </p>
                    </body>
